{
  "doc_id": "5518",
  "text": "Two Argonaute family proteins, Twi1p and Twi11p, are involved in DNA elimination in Tetrahymena. Twi1p is expressed both maternally, from the parental MAC, and zygotically, from the new MAC [CITATION_1] , while Twi11p is expressed only at late conjugation stages, likely exclusively from the new MAC [CITATION_2] . EarlyscnRNAs are loaded into the maternal Twi1p, whose loss causes the destabilization of early-scnRNAs and blocks all early-scnRNA-dependent events, including heterochromatin formation on IESs, the production of late-scnRNAs, and DNA elimination of both types of IESs [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . On the other hand, late-scnRNAs are loaded into zygotic Twi1p and Twi11p. The loss of both zygotic Argonaute proteins results in the destabilization of late-scnRNAs and severe blockage of the elimination of type-B IESs but milder defects in type-A IES elimination [CITATION_6] .",
